				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Thinking about making a bard character<a name="64504"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 27 04 4:21 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Bards are the best character of all, and I say that without any bias at all.
<br />

<br />
QED there are no cons.  Apart from carpal tunnel syndrome.  And the lull/mez/charm hole in the 50's.
<br />

<br />
Some bard songs last longer, so we can twist more than 4 but you need to be some kind of idiot savant to do it.  Twisting 4 reliably, with no dropouts, is the mark of a good bard, imho.
<br />

<br />
We can solo very well without AoE.  Swarming is possible well into the 60's.
<br />

<br />
There's macroing and then there's Macroing...  One is legit and one is not.  It is the Macroing that dare not speak it's name...
<br />

<br />
We can haste, overhaste, slow, DoT, DS, buff resists, Dex, AC, all sorts - have a quick perusal of teh song list on the left there...
<br />

<br />
My advice for a new bard is put all your points into Stamina.  The rest is covered by the guides here.  But learn to twist as soon as you can, and then learn to swarm as soon as you can... prolly not possible at 27 anymore.  The longer charms, DoTs and a good drum make it a bit easier later on.
<br />

<br />
The real secret to being a good bard isn't in the technique - it's in the creativity of the individual player who knows his or her class.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
