			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Thinking about making a bard character<a name="64514"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 27 04 4:53 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Well I am a level 67 bard with 370ish AA in an elemental guild struggling to get into PoTime at the moment. Here is my take on your questions:
<br />

<br />
<b>Bard Downsides/Limitations</b>
<br />

<br />
DPS DPS DPS. We can't put out much DPS. Twisting all the time can make your hands sore and can be boring at times too. Nothing we do lasts very long. So our &quot;tash&quot; (HOS) lasts only three ticks. Although we are a plate class, we don't tank very well. Even if we have the HP and AC to tank in some limited circumstances, we can't hold aggro.
<br />

<br />
<b>Bard Upsides</b>:
<br />

<br />
I do notice that bards are not as much in demand as they once were, but I can't back that up with any data. Some folks think that we are still much in demand. I find that I am wanted in most groups except where they need another DPS toon.
<br />

<br />
Yes, I am often the only slower in a group (PoEarth, BOT, GOD, PoFire). It works pretty well until you get to some crazy GOD or Proving Ground mobs. Remember that bard slow is VERY low aggro and we can land it on a mob when we are bringing it back to camp or if I am not the puller just as it arrives in camp. That fact coupled with being able to add another DPS toon in place of a slower means bard slow is pretty viable in most situations.
<br />

<br />
It is quite fun to play a bard. We can do some pretty crazy things given DA, Fade and being able to cast on the run. In some situations I think bards are better at CC than chanters because we can run and cast and take more hits. Just remember that our mez doesn't last long so we have to keep refreshing it.
<br />

<br />
<b>SOLOING ABILITIES </b> 
<br />

<br />
Bards are traditionally one of the top solo classes. This may be changing from levels 65 to 70, but I don't know yet if that is true. The new charm (level 70) may restore some ability to solo and get decent experience. I can still get decent experience in PON swarming hobgoblins with higher level mobs, but I don't expect that to last when I advance another level.
<br />

<br />
If mobs don't summon, we do have a unique ability to kill most mobs solo. But this may get you some nice loot, but won't get you fast experience.
<br />

<br />
<b>MACRO TWISTING</b>
<br />

<br />
You really can't do it. It won't work unless you are talking abotu a Nostromo Game pad. You can make a key that is :
<br />

<br />
/stop song
<br />
/cast 1
<br />

<br />
and do this for all the songs you will twist. That will cut your key strokes in half. Realistically, you can twist at most four songs. When twisting four songs, it is not possible to avoid one song from dropping from time to time due to server tick, lag and missed notes issues. 
<br />

<br />
<b>STATS FOR A STARTING BARD</b>
<br />

<br />
I know a lot of folks disagree, but I think the best stats to put your points into are DEX and CHARISMA. At the early levels, you will wish you had put the points into stamina for the added HP, but if you can afford decent HP gear this really shouldn't be much of an issue. As you level up, I found that stamina and strength were trivial to rais compared to other stats. Most parses show that charisma (and dex to a lesser extent I think) materially influence the number of your missed notes.  Plus charisma can be harder to max out than other stats. I think that the measure of a bard's power is how many songs (buffs) he can keep on his group or raid. Fewer missed notes means you can keep more songs up longer. More dex and charisma means fewer missed notes. 
<br />

<br />
Anyway I put all my points into dex and charisma and I have never regretted that decision.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Drumm
<br />
67 Bard
<br />
Torv Server</span></td>
