				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Thinking about making a bard character<a name="64515"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 27 04 5:19 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>I agree, but I just wanted to put a few words in edge-wise. 
<br />
The biggest limits on bards don't come from the developers, they come from the folks who play them. The hardest part about being a bard is knowing what to do and when to do it. The routine changes all the time, every group is different and as soon as the group make-up changes, so does your play style. Most bards try to fill in the gaps and would say that is what we're best at, I agree with this somewhat but I argue that a lot of people limit themselves in what they can accomplish, some due to laziness, others due to simply being misinformed. The more you know about <u>all</u> the classes, the better you will do as a bard. The challenge comes in chosing which abilities to augment for the group, which ones to save for important situations (IE Deftdance, FM, DA Song) and which ones to not bother memming because you will constantly be faced with the choice of one song over the other and we all know that hindsight is never 20/20. There are a lot of choices and no matter how hard people try to say &quot;all I do is pull&quot; or &quot;all I do is play mana song&quot; it's just a matter of perspective, if you accept that and limit yourself to it, that's all you're going to be doing. In reality, you're going to experience more variation as a bard than as any other class, forget the fact that we might not be able to do everything as well as everyone else, the only thing that matters is that we <u>can</u> and it's so much fun. 
<br />
Try it you won't regret it. You're going to level from 1-55 very fast but then everything changes, lull and mezz caps start getting to be a real pain, little details like that start forcing you to get very crafty when you pull, especially in LDoNs, or forgo pulling all together in places like PoV until you get to 61. You'll have fun no matter what, just expect some big changes along the way, your role and powers will be constantly shifting as you level.
<br />
The only real way to cover everything is to try it, which I wholeheartedly reccommend, especially if you've played an enchanter, you're already used to puliing your hair out over things like broken mezzes and missed target calls. You'll love it, but if you're losing hair as a chanter already, you might want to go out and just get plugs or a wig before you start playing a bard, maybe some shoulder pads and a helmet so you can bang your head into the wall a few times, it always helps me. 
<br />
And some whiskey.
<br />
</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
