			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Thinking about making a bard character<a name="64520"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Sep 27 04 5:47 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><b>Some bard Downsides:</b>
<br />
1) Minimal feedback - you dont have any gee wiz abilities except selos.  You do what you do and everything goes smoother but no one will ever say things like &quot;wow nice backstab&quot; etc.  It is why many uninformmed people dont think bards are any good (&quot;Bards suxxor!&quot;).
<br />
2) You won't be able to talk to your friends.  If you do you will say things like &quot;k11223344&quot;
<br />
3) The mez hole which hits at 59-61 really hurts - at 61 no one wants me because I cannot mez - One of our strengths is that we can play multiple roles and not having a workable mez in these levels is a pain.
<br />
4) There are a lot of bad bards.  This may change now that AE kiting is dead but the reputation of bards is not good.
<br />
5) bards are hard to play.
<br />

<br />
<b>Benefits:</b>
<br />
1) You will never ever get bored.  You will never want to &lt;insert chore here&gt; while you play eq.  You will always be in the thick of things.
<br />
2) Selos.  Once you get used to it you cannot go back.
<br />
3) You can do really cool stuff - find and watch mitchypoo's movie.
<br />
I have played all tank type classes, cleric and wizard up to the low 50s, then I went back and played my bard in earnest.  I never have gone back.
<br />
4) you are usually the last in your group to die - Our songs generate almost no agro.  To give you an example my druids flame lick stole agro after I slowed, and dotted a mob.  You will never get post mez agro.
<br />

<br />
<b>Groups:</b>
<br />
I have a regular group that I play with on Saturdays.  It consists of two Rogues, SK, Druid, Necro (or monk or shaman) and myself.   I usually pull, haste, slow and CC.  When the monk plays I mana, haste, slow and CC.  There is almost no where we cannot go.
<br />

<br />
I also do guild raids (rarely) and pickup groups.  The key here is to be flexible.  This is where being a bard is hard.  You have to change songs and styles to suit and best benefit your group.  You probably have to change your twist during a battle depending upon how it goes.  Basically, you fill the gaps and to do that you have to know what the gaps are.
<br />

<br />

<br />
<b>My advice to new bards</b>
<br />
For the first 20 levels you are a crappy tank who can run fast.  The 20s define your group abilities with haste, slow, and mez.  The 30s start the solo era and this lasts up until 55 or so if you want.  I would suggest that you group and test out all of your songs.  I also suggest that you group with different people to get a feel for how you play your bard in different situations.  You can get game exp solo but you can only get &quot;Bardly&quot; experience by grouping.
<br />

<br />
Give it a try - you wont regret it.
<br />

<br />
Tin.
<br />
</span></td>
